WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Hi, I'm Gina Reynolds, and my talk is titled,

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:09.000
Who are the ggplot2 extenders and how to become one?

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:13.000
So you may find this title to be a little bit of a bait and switch,

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:17.000
because I'm not going to talk about the extension packages on Crayon,

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:21.000
and who wrote them, and how that connects people, and

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:25.000
who's contributing to what.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:28.000
Although that sounds like a great talk and I'd love to go to it.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:32.000
But I'm going to talk about, instead, this group called the ggplot2 extenders,

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:40.000
which I think you might find maybe even more relevant than that other talk.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:45.000
So this group got started back in 2022,

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:50.000
when I and Jun Choi were talking about ggplot2 extension,

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:55.000
and we really liked extension, but felt that, you know,

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:59.000
it was a bit hard to break into.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:04.000
And for me, at least, it was kind of like being on the outside

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:07.000
of an exclusive club looking in.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:12.000
And so I actually proposed to Jun that we start a club

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:18.000
and maybe change that experience, if not for more people, at least for myself.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:23.000
And Jun agreed.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:28.000
And we started to think about who might else be interested.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:35.000
So we brought on Chun Vonderbrand pretty early on.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:39.000
Jun was aware of his work, and he's been involved since the early days

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:42.000
and continues to be involved, which is really great,

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:49.000
and Jun is a maintainer and developer of ggplot2 itself.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:56.000
So our main activity is to meet virtually and hear from ggplot2 extenders.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:03.000
And right now, we've heard from almost 30 projects, people on their projects.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:09.000
And basically, they go over their motivations for their project,

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:14.000
challenges they face, and kind of how they overcame those challenges.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:16.000
Sometimes we get into the weeds.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:22.000
People kind of throw up GitHub repos and show code, which can be really fun.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:26.000
And there's even more opportunity for that digging into the weeds

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:29.000
over at our discussion page.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:33.000
So you can talk about things in between meetings.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:37.000
So if you're interested in Likert and other diverging bar plots,

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:45.000
that's been a big point of discussion, check out discussion 18.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:52.000
We're also interested in education, and we have some resources for people

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:57.000
to get going with extension that we think could be really helpful

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:00.000
that are going to take you all the way from, like,

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:02.000
something that you probably are familiar with,

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:08.000
like getting a job done in base ggplot2 if you're a ggplot2 user,

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:15.000
all the way to your user-facing function, so geomedians in this case.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:20.000
And as I mentioned, most of our meetings are virtual,

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:24.000
and this means this is great because we can meet with people around the world

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:29.000
pretty regularly, and it's made it easy to record some of our sessions.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:38.000
We have a small library of recorded sessions that you might consider checking out.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:43.000
Very recently, this past August, we have had some in-person interaction,

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:45.000
which has been fun.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:49.000
This is some of our presenters at a panel on extension

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.000
at the Joint Statistical Meeting in Nashville.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:04:01.000
And this past year, Hadley won the graphics award for his work on ggplot2

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:06.000
and other projects, so it was great to celebrate on that as well.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:15.000
We're also interested in Python and the grammar of graphics plot 9 project,

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:21.000
especially. Hasan has presented in our group and often attends,

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:28.000
so extension in that space should be interesting to follow,

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:31.000
and we hope to support that.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:35.000
So that's just a little bit of a background about our group,

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:40.000
and this brings me to the question about how to become a ggplot2 extender.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:45.000
And I'm going to answer in this sense in the context of this group,

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:48.000
and the answer to that question is pretty easy.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:51.000
So you can fill out our join form,

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:56.000
and then we'll be in touch with you about coming to future meetings.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:01.000
And you can check out our website if you're wanting to dig in a little bit deeper

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:06.000
and get a better sense of who we are.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:12.000
And if you want to try some more extension before joining us,

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:19.000
we don't feel like it's a requirement, but you can check out our easy join recipe.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:24.000
And I would say that it is a really great time to join if you're on the fence,

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:34.000
because we're going to have a release party as our next meetup on ggplot2 version 4.0.0.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:42.000
It's going to be Friday, October 3rd, probably at 3 p.m. Eastern.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:50.000
So that is like the main things that I wanted to get across in this talk.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:58.000
Just wanted folks to let more folks know that we exist and that you'd be welcome to join.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:05.000
But I have made maybe a lot of assumptions with that message, right?

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:10.000
It assumes that you're interested in DataVis and ggplot2 and extension.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:17.000
So maybe I should tackle some of those exceptions, and I've got some time, so I'll go ahead and do so.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:21.000
And I'll motivate this part of the talk with a phrase that I'm hearing a lot,

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:29.000
which I'm quoting my son, who we want to learn some Spanish.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:32.000
But you can see that we're having mixed results.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:41.000
So this actually kind of resonates with me.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:45.000
I feel like there's a lot in common with what he's saying.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:52.000
Tell me in my dominant language. Tell me in this non-friction mode of communication, relatively.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:58.000
And the reasons that I'm here.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:02.000
Because I might say something like, tell me visually. Tell me in pictures.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:06.000
I like when people sit me down and show me stuff in schematics.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:10.000
I think it's probably true of a lot of people, right?

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:16.000
Because visualized information is a superhighway.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:21.000
So visual information is pre-attentively processed.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:28.000
We don't have to exert a lot of effort to understand and see patterns in our data, distributions, outliers.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:33.000
All of that stuff is going to happen automatically and effortlessly.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:40.000
So just returning to this language analogy.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:46.000
We are hearing a little bit more of dime en espanol. Tell me a story in Spanish.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:50.000
Talk to me in Spanish, which is great because we don't want to give up on Spanish.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:54.000
I think, you know, having two languages under your belt is really cool.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:57.000
And language is cool in general.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:06.000
And, you know, there's a contrast to experiences between learning English and Spanish.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:08.000
And that can be cool.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:11.000
One of the contrasts is orthography.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.000
How we write stuff down.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:20.000
And in particular, like how we spell stuff.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:25.000
So in English, learning to spell can feel like a battle.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:31.000
Like it's a constant enterprise.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:36.000
You have to learn how to spell new words, word by word.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:41.000
Whereas with Spanish, you kind of learn to spell once.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:46.000
And once you learn to spell, then you can spell things how they sound.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:55.000
And there's kind of a lot of rules that are followed and letters that correspond to sounds.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:59.000
So writing things down and reading them back is very easy in Spanish.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:07.000
And I think that sometimes when you hear about the motivation for ggplot2, it kind of sounds like this to me.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:10.000
I just want to spell my plot how it sounds.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:15.000
And so actually quoting Hadley on his motivation.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.000
He said this.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:20.000
You know, I'd get a data set that I could clearly picture.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:22.000
I'd want to put this on the X axis.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
Let's put this on the Y. Draw a line.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:25.000
Put some points here.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:27.000
Break it up by this variable.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:33.000
And then like getting that vision out of my head and into reality was just really, really hard.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:35.000
Felt harder than it should be.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:37.000
Like there's a lot of custom programming involved.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:49.000
And ggplot2 is really successful in giving us this write it how it sounds kind of experience.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:51.000
We have a data set.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:56.000
We're going to put this variable on the X axis, this variable on the Y axis.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:59.000
Points are going to take on those positions.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:05.000
A line is going to characterize all those positions.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:09.000
And then we can break things up by another variable.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:14.000
So the ggplot2 experience, if I was going to describe it, it's great, right?

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.000
It's easy.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:17.000
It's articulated.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:19.000
It's staccato.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:20.000
Effervescent.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:33.000
It leaves us refreshed after a build instead of like mentally depleted so that we're energized and ready to kind of like make interpretations about the plot that we just built.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.000
It's a great combo, right?

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:36.000
We're in this visual world.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:41.000
So information is processed effortlessly.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:49.000
And ggplot2 makes it almost effortless to build plots.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:52.000
Except for sometimes that's not the case, right?

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
So how do you say this in ggplot2?

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:59.000
There's kind of limits to what you can do with base ggplot2.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:05.000
And, you know, at first building this plot is pretty staccato.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:17.000
But then when I want to draw a line at the mean, it does require a fair amount of thinking and thinking things through.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:19.000
And how would you say this?

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:27.000
Well, if you want to look at group means, then you might be doing some precomputation.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:35.000
And then when you go ahead and plot those means, it also the code is a little bit verbose.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:41.000
So what happens when ggplot2 isn't refreshing?

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:49.000
An extender might step in and write up something that's a little bit more effervescent and bubbly.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:54.000
And that doesn't need to be like a very serious endeavor, especially when you're joining our group.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:58.000
We're not going to push you to write a package right away.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:04.000
You can just be playful with your extensions, too.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:08.000
But an extension in this scenario might look like this.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:11.000
Geom xmean.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:17.000
And then for free, we get that group-wise computation.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:21.000
OK, so I covered kind of these assumptions.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:34.000
I hope you're convinced that dataviz, ggplot2, and extension are all worthwhile and should be on your radar.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:45.000
But one more question that you might have about the extenders is like, are you just a group of enthusiasts or are things getting done in this group?

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:52.000
And I actually wish that I were spending more time on this part of the talk.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:13:00.000
But I'll just turn to this example, which is from a new package called ggsprings.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:12.000
And it lets you kind of reflect on this fact that there's actually a lot in common between our regression models and the physical world.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:21.000
So Hooke's law could be in play if there were springs attached to these points.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:31.000
And there's a great blog post that Michael Friendly, who is the author of this package, was aware of by Joshua Luftus.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:51.000
And Joshua took some of the extension content from the ggplot2 extension chapter of the ggplot2 book and wrote a nice blog post about this fact.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:14:01.000
But Michael said, well, why isn't there a package for that? And wouldn't it be nice to have that available in a package shop?

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:11.000
And he had just joined our group and had some questions about the specifics about how to do this.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:29.000
And I think we were able to provide a lot of information and help in this project to make it that much stronger in the way of how to package in the ggplot2 context.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:36.000
And also how to make some of the functions a bit more comfortable for use in the context that you imagine.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:54.000
So you can imagine these functions being usable even by both instructors and students themselves if they were kind of passionate about these parallels that are happening between physical phenomenon and the stats world.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:15:07.000
So that does bring me to the close of the talk. And I'll just close by saying I think I'm really excited to be a part of this group myself.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:24.000
And the membership is what makes the group so strong. And I think that your joining us could potentially be a real boon to this group.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:34.000
So I hope you'll consider it and enjoy ggplot2 extension that does come out of this group.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:39.000
Thanks so much and looking forward to the Q&A.

